{"timestamp": "2025-11-28 16:39:00.878213", "event": "llm_start", "prompts": ["System: You are an expert network engineer.\nYour task is to submit the final solution for this network problem based on the diagnosis reported provided.\nCarefully review the diagnosis results and ensure that your submission is accurate and complete.\nYou must strictly follow the submission format and call the submit() tool to submit your solution.\nHuman: Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report — multi‑tier Clos EBGP fabric\nSummary\n- Overall status: Network is operational. Host‑to‑host reachability is successful (pc_0_0 → pc_0_1 pings OK). All routers have BGP sessions in Established state and the expected /24 host prefixes are present in router RIBs.\n- One notable abnormality (no outage observed): a prefix‑count mismatch on the session between spine_router_0_1 (AS 65101) and super_spine_router_0 (AS 65000): the super spine shows it has sent prefixes to the spine, but the spine reports 0 accepted prefixes from that neighbor. Analysis indicates this is due to normal BGP AS‑path loop prevention (super has a path that contains spine's AS) rather than a control‑plane failure.\n\nEvidence & findings (collected data)\n1) Host reachability\n- Reachability test (pc_0_0 → pc_0_1): 4 pings, 0% loss, RTT avg ≈ 2.844 ms.\n  Source: reachability probe results: \"pc_0_0 → pc_0_1: tx 4 rx 4 loss_percent 0.0\".\n\n2) Interface / addressing (selected)\n- pc_0_0: eth0 10.0.0.2/24, gateway 10.0.0.1\n- pc_0_1: eth0 10.0.1.2/24, gateway 10.0.1.1\n- leaf_router_0_0: eth2 10.0.0.1/24; inter‑router links eth0 172.16.0.5/31, eth1 172.16.0.9/31\n- leaf_router_0_1: eth2 10.0.1.1/24; inter‑router links eth0 172.16.0.7/31, eth1 172.16.0.11/31\n- spine_router_0_0: inter‑router 172.16.0.1/31, 172.16.0.4/31, 172.16.0.6/31\n- spine_router_0_1: inter‑router 172.16.0.3/31, 172.16.0.8/31, 172.16.0.10/31\n- super_spine_router_0: inter‑router 172.16.0.0/31, 172.16.0.2/31\n\n(Interface outputs confirm links are up and IP addressing matches the expected /31 interconnects and /24 host subnets.)\n\n3) BGP sessions and routes\n- All expected EBGP neighbors are in Established state (FRR summaries):\n  - leaf_router_0_0 peers: 172.16.0.4 (spine_router_0_0) and 172.16.0.8 (spine_router_0_1) — both up.\n  - leaf_router_0_1 peers: 172.16.0.6 (spine_router_0_0) and 172.16.0.10 (spine_router_0_1) — both up.\n  - spine_router_0_0 peers: 172.16.0.0 (super), 172.16.0.5 (leaf 0_0), 172.16.0.7 (leaf 0_1) — up.\n  - spine_router_0_1 peers: 172.16.0.2 (super), 172.16.0.9 (leaf 0_0), 172.16.0.11 (leaf 0_1) — up.\n  - super_spine_router_0 peers: 172.16.0.1 (spine 0_0) and 172.16.0.3 (spine 0_1) — up.\n- Host prefixes are present in routing tables (examples):\n  - leaf_router_0_0 routes: 10.0.0.0/24 directly connected, 10.0.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.8 (bgp)\n  - leaf_router_0_1 routes: 10.0.1.0/24 directly connected, 10.0.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.10 (bgp)\n  - spine routers and super_spine have learned 10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24 (BGP) with next hops pointing to the appropriate leaf/spine IPs.\n\n4) The anomaly / oddity (localized)\n- On spine_router_0_1 (local AS 65101), the detailed BGP neighbor output for neighbor 172.16.0.2 (super_spine_router_0) shows: \"For address family: IPv4 Unicast ... 0 accepted prefixes\".\n- At the same time, super_spine_router_0's BGP summary shows it has PfxSnt=2 to neighbor 172.16.0.3 (spine_router_0_1).\n- The spine_router_0_1's own BGP table still contains the two host prefixes (10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24) learned via its leaf neighbors (next hops 172.16.0.9 and 172.16.0.11). So traffic forwarding is unaffected.\n\nLocalization of issue\n- The observation is localized to the control‑plane interaction between:\n  - spine_router_0_1 (172.16.0.3, AS 65101) and\n  - super_spine_router_0 (172.16.0.2, AS 65000).\n- Specifically: super_spine reports sending prefixes to spine_router_0_1, but spine_router_0_1 reports it accepted 0 prefixes from that neighbor.\n\nRoot cause analysis (why the mismatch)\n- The BGP tables show AS paths that include the spine's own AS (65101) in the path super_spine learned. Example: super_spine has a path for 10.0.0.0/24 whose AS path contains 65101 (originated by spine_router_0_1 originally). When the super spine attempts to advertise that path back to spine_router_0_1, the prefix would contain spine_router_0_1's AS in the AS_PATH attribute. BGP loop prevention semantics prevent accepting routes that have the local AS already present in AS_PATH. Consequently, spine_router_0_1 rejects (does not accept) those particular paths — producing the \"0 accepted prefixes\" count for that neighbor even though super_spine sent updates.\n- In short: the mismatch is explained by expected AS‑path loop prevention behavior (the super spine has multiple paths and one of them contains the spine's AS, which the spine will not accept). This is a control‑plane policy/loop‑avoidance phenomenon rather than an operational failure.\n\nImpact\n- No data‑plane impact observed: host ping succeeded (0% loss). All routers have working routes for the hosts and forwarding is functional.\n- Control‑plane visibility: the PfxRcd/PfxSnt counters can look inconsistent between peers because of AS‑path loop prevention, but this does not indicate a broken BGP session.\n\nConclusion\n- Network health: healthy / operational.\n- Anomaly: prefix count mismatch on the session super_spine_router_0 ↔ spine_router_0_1 (spine reports 0 accepted prefixes while super reports sending 2).\n- Root cause: behavior consistent with BGP AS‑path loop prevention (super spine advertising a path that contains spine_router_0_1’s AS; spine drops it). Not an actual failure; expected BGP behavior in a multi‑path environment when routes originated by a peer would be re‑advertised back and rejected by AS‑path checks.\n- Localization: control‑plane interaction between super_spine_router_0 and spine_router_0_1. No faulty physical interfaces or adjacency down events detected.\n\nIf you want, I can:\n- show the exact BGP AS_PATH lines from the super_spine and spine tables to illustrate the AS sequence that triggers the loop prevention; or\n- run additional checks (e.g., explicit \"show bgp ipv4 unicast\" outputs or neighbor-specific show commands) to further document which neighbor advertised which path., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available."], "metadata": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
